    <name>
      <text>Equation of an Ellipse with Given Foci and Major Axis</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<br> Find the equation of the ellipse with focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{2} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\), and major axis \( AA'={@AA@}  \).
<br>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked solution</h3>
<br> Find the equation of the ellipse with focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{2} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and major axis \( AA'={@AA@}  \).
<br> The equation of an ellipse in standard form follows:
 <br>\[ \displaystyle \frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1\]
<br> Here the center is \(O (h, k)\). 
<br> In addtion, if \(\displaystyle F_{1} (x_{F_{1}}, y_{F_{1}})\) and \(\displaystyle F_{2} (x_{F_{2}}, y_{F_{2}}) \) are the focus, and  \( AA'={@AA@}  \)  the major axis, we let \(F_{1}F_{2}=2\cdot c\). 
<br> We suppose that \(F_{1}F_{2} \) is computed along \( y-axis\), that is,  \( a < b\).
<br> Then we have the following relations:
<br>\(
(1) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
2 \cdot a = AA' \\ 
b^2=a^2 + c^2
\end{array}\right. \) 
<br> Since \(O\) midpoint of \( F_{1} F_{2} \), then  \( (2) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h= \displaystyle \frac{x_{F_{1}}+x_{F_{2}}}{2}\\ 
k= \displaystyle \frac{y_{F_{1}}+y_{F_{2}}}{2}
\end{array}\right. \) 
<br> In this case, focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{2} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and \( AA'= {@AA@}  \).
<br>Using the information above we have
<br> \(2 \cdot c =|y_{F_{1}}-y_{F_{2}}|=|({@focus1_y@})-({@focus2_y@})|={@cc@} \implies c = {@c@}\), and \( AA'= {@AA@} \)
<br> The system (1) becomes: <br>\(
\left\{ \begin{array}{r}
a= \displaystyle {@val_a@}\\ 
b= \displaystyle {@val_b@}
\end{array}\right.\) 
<br> Using the system (2), we get 
\( \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h= \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_x@})+({@focus2_x@})}{2} = {@h@} \\ 
k= \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_y@})+({@focus2_y@})}{2} = {@k@}
\end{array}\right. \) 
<br> Therefore, the equation of the ellipse is:
<br> \( \displaystyle {@ta1@} \)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
